The show has also allowed people to see a side of him that many probably never knew existed. I do believe, as he says, the older heâ€™s gotten the more settled and unguarded he has become. It was actually quite touching to hear how his mother and father were so emotional when he was working on the album. For whatever reason I have just always had in my head that his parents were A little harsh, and a little cold with him. I know in the beginning they did not support him but I think now of course all is well. I look forward to each episode of his show, because not only do we get discover the character of his guests, but we also get glimpses of little layers of him as well. He always tells us something different in his stories. I really admire and respect him so much, not only as an artist, but in the way he thinks as a person. It is easy to see why all seven members get along so well, and are truly brothers to one another. Each one of them are really completely different, yet their personalities really have mashed into one, and I really canâ€™t imagine one without the otherâ€¦ Kind of like their DNA choreography chain. I look forward to his future episodes, and hope we get many more before his time to leave for duty.

author: @jess7613
text: There is something so endlessly endearing about such genuine conversations like this. Being a similar age and mindset to Yoongi, I feel so relieved watching these kinds of conversations. I don't have my life figured out, but I am learning more and more about life and people and growth everyday. Living with a calm and steadiness, but also reclaiming passion and drive and dreams. I genuinely can't thank Yoongi, BTS, and the Suchwita guests enough. Growing up is confusing and challenging but it's also a gift. To grow old, to continue to learn, to love and to lose. If anything, I have learned over the past few years, it's a true blessing to be an ARMY. Because I have gained so much since that fateful day. And Yoongi, I think you are strong. We all have strength and weaknesses. It's how we choose to overcome our own challenges is what makes true strength. Strength is also gentleness, tenderness. You and the guys and all ARMY who read this have such immense strength. I am so proud of you all. In a way, perceived weakness is strength too.

author: @BM-ur4je
text: I have truly enjoyed all the Suchwita episodes. But this one and the one with RM when he divulges his major challenges in composing his 3rd part documentary and album truly reveal an amazing introspective, insightful, sensitive to almost painful levels and deeply intelligent AND high EQ person who doesn't fear increasingly revealing more of his authentic person. I also feel that the North American solo tour he has just completed with tremendous success which possibly surprised him above his expectations, has opened a dormant compartment in his soul permitting him to 'feel soft' and express his vulnerability in ways he has not done before. This has been a poignant moment in getting to know Yoongi more deeply. I feel he would make a great youth counsellor for South Koreans. He is de facto accomplishing this not only through his musical compositions but increasingly and with greater freedom in his varied public showings now that the band is temporarily on hiatus. I am so proud of these 7 wonderful boys-turned-men developing into remarkably sensitive authentic adults without the negative trappings of celebrity that are such a staple of most celebrities both in the West as well as in Asian countries (I'm thinking more of the Chinese and Indian 'stars').

text: I agree. This was more of a conversation, and there weren't any games or "gotcha" questions.  Yoongi is really a skilled interviewer, and he puts people at ease...and I also love that he answers his own question first to give the other person either time to think about what they want to say OR to simply react to his answer if they don't want to provide anything about themselves.  He is a genuine and lovely person, truly.

author: @TallieRS2378
text:
I enjoyed this episode. It was really refreshing. It is true, seeing people, celebrity or not, be their authentic self is amazing. As much as I love BTS music collectively and individually, what ultimately drew me in as a fan were the times they were just being themselves. Watching Run BTS, watching clips of old concerts where the members are just interacting with each other, the vlives/weverse lives and interviews, behind the scenes of music videos, were all moments we got to see BTS as Kim Namjoon, Kim Seokjin, Min Yoongi, Jung Hoseok, Park  Jimin, Kim Taehyung and Jeon Jungkook and not their personas. I love seeing those moments.

Hope this series can continue even after they all return from their enlistment.
